# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: price-of-anarchy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] The paradox may have analogies in electrical power grids and biological systems.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] It has been suggested that, in theory, the improvement of a malfunctioning network could be accomplished by removing certain parts of it.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] The paradox has been used to explain instances of improved traffic flow when existing major roads are closed.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Dietrich Braess, a mathematician at Ruhr University, Germany, noticed the flow in a road network could be impeded by adding a new road, when he was working on traffic modelling.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] His idea was that if each driver is making the optimal self-interested decision as to which route is quickest, a shortcut could be chosen too often for drivers to have the shortest travel times possible.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] More formally, the idea behind Braess's discovery is that the Nash equilibrium may not equate with the best overall flow through a network.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Adding extra capacity to a network when the moving entities selfishly choose their route can in some cases reduce overall performance.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] That is because the Nash equilibrium of such a system is not necessarily optimal.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] The network change induces a new game structure which leads to a (multiplayer) prisoner's dilemma.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] In a Nash equilibrium, drivers have no incentive to change their routes.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] While the system is not in a Nash equilibrium, individual drivers are able to improve their respective travel times by changing the routes they take.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] In the case of Braess's paradox, drivers will continue to switch until they reach Nash equilibrium despite the reduction in overall performance.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] If the latency functions are linear, adding an edge can never make total travel time at equilibrium worse by a factor of more than 4/3.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Braess's paradox has a counterpart in case of a reduction of the road network, which may cause a reduction of individual commuting time.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] In Seoul, South Korea, traffic around the city sped up when the Cheonggye Expressway was removed as part of the Cheonggyecheon restoration project.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] In Stuttgart, Germany, after investments into the road network in 1969, the traffic situation did not improve until a section of newly built road was closed for traffic again.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] In 1990 the temporary closing of 42nd Street in Manhattan, New York City, for Earth Day reduced the amount of congestion in the area.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] In 2008 Youn, Gastner and Jeong demonstrated specific routes in Boston, New York City and London where that might actually occur and pointed out roads that could be closed to reduce predicted travel times.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] In 2009, New York experimented with closures of Broadway at Times Square and Herald Square, which resulted in improved traffic flow and permanent pedestrian plazas.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] In 2012, Paul Lecroart, of the institute of planning and development of the Île-de-France, wrote that "Despite initial fears, the removal of main roads does not cause deterioration of traffic conditions beyond the starting adjustments.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] The traffic transfer are limited and below expectations".
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] He also notes that some private vehicle trips (and related economic activity) are not transferred to public transport and simply disappear ("evaporate").
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] The same phenomenon was also observed when road closing was not part of an urban project but the consequence of an accident.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] In 2012 in Rouen, a bridge was destroyed by fire.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Over the next two years, other bridges were used more, but the total number of cars crossing bridges was reduced.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Consider a road network on which 4000 drivers wish to travel from a Start point to an End point.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] They have two roads available to choose from, one that goes via point A and one that goes via point B.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] The travel time in minutes from the Start to point A is the number of travellers (T) divided by 100, and the time to point B is a constant 45 minutes.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] These times are then reversed for the routes to the End point: from point A to the End point takes 45 minutes, and from B to the End point takes ${\tfrac {T}{100}}$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] If these are the only routes available, the time needed to drive Start–A–End route with a drivers would be ${\tfrac {a}{100}}+45$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] The time needed to drive the Start–B–End route with b drivers would be ${\tfrac {b}{100}}+45$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] As there are 4000 drivers, the fact that $a+b=4000$ can be used to derive the fact that $a=b=2000$ when the system is at equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] If either route took less time, it would not be a Nash equilibrium: a rational driver would switch from the longer route to the shorter route.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Now suppose a new road was built connecting points A and B, with an extremely short travel time of approximately 0 minutes.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Suppose that the road is opened and one driver tries Start–A–B–End.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Soon, more of the 4000 drivers are trying this new route.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] The time taken rises from 40.01 and keeps climbing.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] When the number of drivers trying the new route reaches 2500, with 1500 still in the Start–B–End route, their time will be ${\tfrac {2500}{100}}+{\tfrac {4000}{100}}=65$ minutes, which is no improvement over the original route.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Nobody has any incentive to travel A-End or Start-B because any driver trying them will take 85 minutes.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Thus, the opening of the cross route triggers an irreversible change to it by everyone, costing everyone 80 minutes instead of the original 65.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] If every driver were to agree not to use the A–B path, or if that route were closed, every driver would benefit by a 15-minute reduction in travel time.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] If one assumes the travel time for each person driving on an edge to be equal, an equilibrium will always exist.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Let $L_{e}(x)$ be the formula for the travel time of each person traveling along edge e when x people take that edge.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Suppose there is a traffic graph with $x_{e}$ people driving along edge e .
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Let the total energy of the traffic graph be the sum of the energies of every edge in the graph.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Take a choice of routes that minimizes the total energy.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Such a choice must exist because there are finitely many choices of routes.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Assume, for contradiction, this is not the case.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Then, there is at least one driver who can switch the route and improve the travel time.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Let E be total energy of the traffic graph, and consider what happens when the route $e_{0},e_{1},...e_{n}$ is removed.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] That is simply the total travel time needed to take the original route.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] If the new route is then added, $e'_{0},e'_{1},\ldots ,e'_{m}$ , the total energy E will be increased by the total travel time needed to take the new route.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Because the new route is shorter than the original route, E must decrease relative to the original configuration, contradicting the assumption that the original set of routes minimized the total energy.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Therefore, the choice of routes minimizing total energy is an equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] The above proof outlines a procedure known as best response dynamics, which finds an equilibrium for a linear traffic graph and terminates in a finite number of steps.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] The algorithm is termed "best response" because at each step of the algorithm, if the graph is not at equilibrium then some driver has a best response to the strategies of all other drivers and switches to that response.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] At each step, if some particular driver could do better by taking an alternate path (a "best response"), doing so strictly decreases the energy of the graph.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] If no driver has a best response, the graph is at equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Since the energy of the graph strictly decreases with each step, the best response dynamics algorithm must eventually halt.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] If the travel time functions are linear, that is $L_{e}(x)=a_{e}x+b_{e}$ for some $a_{e},b_{e}\geq 0$ , then at worst, traffic in the energy-minimizing equilibrium is twice as bad as socially optimal.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Proof: Let Z be some traffic configuration, with associated energy $E(Z)$ and total travel time $T(Z)$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] For each edge, the energy is the sum of an arithmetic progression, and using the formula for the sum of an arithmetic progression, one can show that $E(Z)\leq T(Z)\leq 2E(Z)$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] If $Z_{o}$ is the socially-optimal traffic flow and $Z_{e}$ is the energy-minimizing traffic flow, the inequality implies that $T(Z_{e})\leq 2E(Z_{e})\leq 2E(Z_{o})\leq 2T(Z_{o})$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Thus, the total travel time for the energy-minimizing equilibrium is at most twice as bad as for the optimal flow.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Mlichtaich proved that Braess's paradox occurs in a two-terminal network if and only if it is not a series-parallel graph.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] In 1983, Steinberg and Zangwill provided, under reasonable assumptions, the necessary and sufficient conditions for Braess's paradox to occur in a general transportation network when a new route is added.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] (Note that their result applies to the addition of *any* new route, not just to the case of adding a single link.) As a corollary, they obtain that Braess's paradox is about as likely to occur as not occur when a random new route is added.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] In 2012, scientists at the Max Planck Institute for Dynamics and Self-Organization demonstrated, through computational modelling, the potential for the phenomenon to occur in power transmission networks where power generation is decentralized.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] In 2012, an international team of researchers from Institut Néel (CNRS, France), INP (France), IEMN (CNRS, France) and UCL (Belgium) published in *Physical Review Letters* a paper showing that Braess's paradox may occur in mesoscopic electron systems.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] In particular, they showed that adding a path for electrons in a nanoscopic network paradoxically reduced its conductance.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] That was shown both by simulations as well as experiments at low temperature using scanning gate microscopy.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] A model with springs and ropes can show that a hung weight can rise in height despite a taut rope in the hanging system being cut, and follows from the same mathematical structure as the original Braess's paradox.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] For two identical springs joined in series by a short rope, their total spring constant is half of each individual spring, resulting in a long stretch when a certain weight is hung.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] This remains the case as we add two longer ropes in slack to connect the lower end of the upper spring to the hung weight (lower end of the lower spring), and the upper end of the lower spring to the hanging point (upper end of the upper spring).
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] However, when the short rope is cut, the longer ropes become taut, and the two springs become parallel (in the mechanical sense) to each other.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] The total spring constant is twice that of each individual spring, and when the length of the long ropes is not too long, the hung weight will actually be higher compared to before the short rope was cut.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] The fact that the hung weight rises despite cutting a taut rope (the short rope) in the hanging system is counter-intuitive, but it does follow from Hooke's law and the way springs work in series and in parallel.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Motter and collaborators demonstrated that Braess's paradox outcomes may often occur in biological and ecological systems.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Motter suggests removing part of a perturbed network could rescue it.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] For resource management of endangered species food webs, in which extinction of many species might follow sequentially, selective removal of a doomed species from the network could in principle bring about the positive outcome of preventing a series of further extinctions.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] A proposed solution for maximum efficiency in scoring is for a star player to shoot about the same number of shots as teammates.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] However, this approach is not supported by hard statistical evidence, as noted in the original paper.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Braess's paradox has been shown to appear in blockchain payment channel networks, also known as layer-2 networks.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Payment channel networks implement a solution to the scalability problem of blockchain networks, allowing transactions of high rates without recording them on the blockchain.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] In such a network, users can establish a channel by locking funds on each side of the channel.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] Transactions are executed either through a channel connecting directly the payer and payee or through a path of channels with intermediate users that ask for some fees.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] While intuitively, opening new channels allows higher routing flexibility, adding a new channel might cause higher fees, and similarly closing existing channels might decrease fees.
[src:price-of-anarchy/braess-s-paradox] The paper presented a theoretical analysis with conditions for the paradox, methods for mitigating the paradox as well as an empirical analysis, showing the appearance in practice of the paradox and its effects on Bitcoin's Lightning network.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] The research of congestion games was initiated by the American economist Robert W.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] He proved that every congestion game has a Nash equilibrium in pure strategies (aka *pure Nash equilibrium*, PNE).
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] During the proof, he in fact proved that every congestion game is an exact potential game.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Later, Monderer and Shapley proved a converse result: any game with an exact potential function is equivalent to some congestion game.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Consider a traffic net where two players originate at point O and need to get to point T.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Suppose that node O is connected to node T via two paths: *O*-*A*-*T* and *O*-*B*-*T*, where A is a little closer than B (i.e.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] A is more likely to be chosen by each player), as in the picture at the right.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] The roads from both connection points to T get easily congested, meaning the more players pass through a point, the greater the delay of each player becomes, so having both players go through the same connection point causes extra delay.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Formally, the delay in each of *A**T* and *B**T* when x players go there is $x^{2}$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] A good outcome in this game will be for the two players to "coordinate" and pass through different connection points.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] The pure Nash equilibria in this game are (OAT,OBT) and (OBT,OAT): any unilateral change by one of the players increases the cost of this player (note that the values in the table are costs, so players prefer them to be smaller).
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] In this example, the Nash equilibrium is *efficient* - the players choose different lanes and the sum of costs is minimal.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] In contrast, suppose the delay in each of AT and BT when x players go there is $0.8x$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Now, the only pure Nash equilibrium is ⁠ $(OAT,OAT)$ ⁠: any player switching to OBT increases his cost from 2.6 to 2.8.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] An equilibrium still exists, but it is not efficient: the sum of costs is 5.2, while the sum of cost in ⁠ $(OAT,OBT)$ ⁠ and ⁠ $(OBT,OAT)$ ⁠ is 4.6.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] The basic definition of a CG has the following components.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Every CG has a Nash equilibrium in pure strategies.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] This can be shown by constructing a *potential function* that assigns a value to each outcome.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Moreover, this construction will also show that iterated best response finds a Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Note that this function is *not* the social welfare $\textstyle \sum _{e\in E}x_{e}d_{e}(x_{e})$ , but rather a discrete integral of sorts.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] The critical property of a potential function for a congestion game is that if one player switches strategy, the change in his delay is equal to the change in the potential function.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Consider the case when player i switches from $P_{i}$ to $Q_{i}$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Elements that are in both of the strategies remain unaffected, elements that the player leaves (i.e. $e\in P_{i}-Q_{i}$ ) decrease the potential by $d_{e}(x_{e})$ , and the elements the player joins (i.e. $e\in Q_{i}-P_{i}$ ) increase the potential by $d_{e}(x_{e}+1)$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] This change in potential is precisely the change in delay for player i, so $\Phi$ is in fact a potential function.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Now observe that any minimum of $\Phi$ is a pure Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Fixing all but one player, any improvement in strategy by that player corresponds to decreasing $\Phi$ , which cannot happen at a minimum.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Now since there are a finite number of configurations and each $d_{e}$ is monotone, there exists an equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] The existence of a potential function has an additional implication, called the **finite improvement property (FIP)**.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] If we start with any strategy-vector, pick a player arbitrarily, and let him change his strategy to a better strategy for him, and repeat, then the sequence of improvements must be finite (that is, the sequence will not cycle).
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] This is because each such improvement strictly increases the potential.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Below we present various extensions and variations on the basic CG model.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] A **nonatomic** **CG** is the limit of a standard CG with *n* players, as $n\rightarrow \infty$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] As in any nonatomic game, there is a continuum of players, the players are considered "infinitesimally small", and each individual player has a negligible effect on the congestion.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Nonatomic CGs were studied by Milchtaich, Friedman, Blonsky, and Roughgarden and Tardos.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Strategies are now collections of strategy profiles $f_{P}$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] For a strategy set $S_{i}$ of size n, the collection of all valid profiles is a compact subset of $[0,r_{i}]^{n}$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] We now define the potential function as $\textstyle \Phi =\sum _{e\in E}\int _{0}^{x_{e}}d_{e}(z)\,dz$ , replacing the discrete integral with the standard one.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] As a function of the strategy, $\Phi$ is continuous: $d_{e}$ is continuous by assumption, and $x_{e}$ is a continuous function of the strategy.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Then by the extreme value theorem, $\Phi$ attains its global minimum.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] The final step is to show that a minimum of $\Phi$ is indeed a Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Assume for contradiction that there exists a collection of $f_{P}$ that minimize $\Phi$ but are not a Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Then for some type i, there exists some improvement $Q\in S_{i}$ over the current choice P.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] The idea now is to take a small amount $\delta <f_{P}$ of players using strategy P and move them to strategy Q.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Now for any $x_{e}\in Q$ , we have increased its load by $\delta$ , so its term in $\Phi$ is now $\textstyle \int _{0}^{x_{e}+\delta }d_{e}(z)dz$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Differentiating the integral, this change is approximately $\delta \cdot d_{e}(x_{e})$ , with error $\delta ^{2}$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] The equivalent analysis of the change holds when we look at edges in P.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Therefore, the change in potential is approximately $\textstyle \delta (\sum _{e\in Q}d_{e}(x_{e})-\sum _{e\in P}d_{e}(x_{e}))$ , which is less than zero.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] This is a contradiction, as then $\Phi$ was not minimized.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Therefore, a minimum of $\Phi$ must be a Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] In a **splittable CG** (also called **atomic splittable CG**), as in an atomic CG, there are finitely many players, each of whom has a certain load to transfer.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] As in a nonatomic CG, each player can split his load into fractional loads going through different paths, like a transportation company choosing a set of paths for mass transportation.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] In contrast to a nonatomic CG, each player has a non-negligible effect on the congestion.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Splittable CGs were first analyzed by Ariel Orda, Raphael Rom and Nachum Shimkin in 1993, in the context of communication networks.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] They show that, for a simple network with two nodes and multiple parallel links, the Nash equilibrium is unique under reasonable convexity conditions, and has some interesting monotonicity properties.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] For general network topologies, more complex conditions are required to guarantee the uniqueness of Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] In parallel, Haurie and Marcotte studied splittable CGs in the context of transportation networks.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] They defined a Nash-Cournot equilibrium and provided conditions for its existence and uniqueness.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] They showed that, under reasonable conditions, the asymptotic behavior of this NE yield a total flow vector corresponding to a Wardrop equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] The price of anarchy in splittable CGs was studied by Gairing, Monien and Tiemann, Cominetti, Correa and Stier-Moses, Harks, and finally Roughgarden and Schoppmann.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Huang studies the effect of collusion on the social cost in splittable CGs.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] He shows that if the network satifies some natural structural condition, and all delay functions are affine, then collusion decreases the social cost in equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] But if either of these conditions is not satisfied, collusion might decrease the social cost.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Richman and Shimkin characterize the networks that guarantee that every splittable CG has a unique PNE.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Harks and Timmermans also study equilibrium uniqueness in atomic splittable polymatroid CGs.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Marcotte presented four numeric algorithms for computing NE on congested transportation networks, and analyzed their convergence properties.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Meunier and Pradeau presented a numeric algorithm, similar to the Lemke-Howson algorithm, for nonatomic network CGs with affine player-specific delay functions.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Both these numeric algorithms were not shown to run in polynomial time.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Cominetti, Correa and Stier-Moses studied splittable CGs with affine player-independent delay functions: $d_{e,i}(x)=a_{e}\cdot x_{e}+b_{e}$ , where *xe* is the load on edge *e*, and *ae*,*be* are player-independent constants.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] They showed a convex potential function whose global minima are PNE.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] This means that epsilon-approximate PNEs can be computed in polytime by convex programming.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Huang also considered affine player-independent delay functions.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] He devised a combinatorial algorithm computing an exact PNE for splittable CGs on symmetric graphs that satisfy a natural structural condition he calls "well-designed" (for example, series–parallel graphs).
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Bhaskar and Lolakapuri considered splittable network CGs with convex player-independent delay functions.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] They presented two algorithms for computing approximate PNE: the first is exponential in the number of players, and while the second is exponential in the number of edges.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] They also show that in general networks, it is NP-hard to decide if there exists a PNE where every player has cost at most some given constant *C*.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Klimm and Warode studied atomic splittable network CGs with affine player-specific delay functions $d_{e,i}(x)=a_{e,i}\cdot x_{e}+b_{e,i}$ , where *xe* is the load on edge *e*, and *aei*, *bei* are player-specific constants.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] They proved that computing a PNE is PPAD-complete.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Harks and Timmermans study splittable atomic CGs with singleton strategy sets - each player should split his load among the edges (not among the paths).
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] This corresponds to a network of *m* parallel edges between the source and the target.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] They allow player-specific delay functions.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] The total cost suffered by each player *i* is $\sum _{e}x_{i,e}\cdot d_{e,i}(x)$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] They present an algorithm for computing a PNE in time $O((nm)^{3}+n^{2}m^{14}\log(D/k_{0}))$ , where *n* is the number of players, *m* the number of edges, *D* is the maximum player-specific demand, and *k*0 the smallest packet size.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] They also note that computing a PNE in atomic splittable CGs with singleton strategies and affine delay funcions can be presented as a Linear complementarity problem.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] In a **weighted** **CG**, different players may have different effects on the congestion.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] For example, in a road network, a truck adds congestion much more than a motorcycle.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Whereas an unweighted CG is an anonymous game, a weighted CG is not anonymous, as the payoff of a player depends not only on the number of players who take each action, but also on their weight.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] In general, the weight of a player may depend on the resource (**resource-specific weights**): for every player *i* and resource *e*, there is weight $w_{i,e}$ , and the load on the resource *e* is $x_{e}=\sum _{i:e\in P_{i}}w_{i,e}$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] An important special case is when the weight depends only on the player (**resource-independent weights**), that is, each player i has a weight $w_{i}$ , and $x_{e}=\sum _{i:e\in P_{i}}w_{i}$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Milchtaich considered the special case of weighted CGs in which each strategy is a single resource ("singleton CG"), the weights are *resource-independent*, and all players have the same strategy set.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Milchtaich considered the special case of weighted CGs in which each strategy is a path in a given undirected graph ("network CG").
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] He proved that every finite game can be represented as a weighted network congestion game, with nondecreasing (but not necessarily negative) cost-functions.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] This implies that not every such game has a PNE.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Concrete examples of weighted CGs without PNE are given by Libman and Orda, as well as Goemans Mirrokni and Vetta.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] This raises the question of what conditions guarantee the existence of PNE.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] In particular, we say that a certain graph *G guarantees* a certain property if every weighted network CG in which the underlying network is *G* has that property.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Milchtaich characterized networks that guarantee the existence of PNE, as well as the finite-improvement property, with the additional condition that a player with a lower weight has weakly more allowed strategies (formally, $w_{i}<w_{j}$ implies $|S_{i}|\geq |S_{j}|$ ).
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] In the special case in which every player is allowed to use any strategy ("public edges"), there are more networks that guarantee the existence of PNE; a complete characterization of such networks is posed as an open problem.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Holzman and Law-Yone also characterize the networks that guarantee that every atomic CG has a strong PNE, a unique PNE, or a Pareto-efficient PNE.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Richman and Shimkin characterize the networks that guarantee that every *splittable* CG has a unique PNE.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] We say that a class *C* of functions *guarantees* a certain property if every weighted CG in which all delay functions are elements of *C* has that property.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Gairing, Monien and Tiemann study weighted network CGs with player-specific delays.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] They consider both splittable and unsplittable flows.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] When the delay functions are linear (without a constant term, that is *be*=0), they introduce two new potential functions and derive results on computation of PNE.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] There are many other papers about weighted congestion games.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] The basic CG model can be extended by allowing the delay function of each resource to depend on the player.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] So for each resource *e* and player *i*, there is a delay function $d_{i,e}$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Given a strategy $P_{i}$ , player i experiences delay $\textstyle \sum _{e\in P_{i}}d_{i,e}(x_{e})$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] This special case of CG is also called a **crowding game**.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] It represents a setting in which several people simultaneously choose a place to go to (e.g. a room, a settlement, a restaurant), and their payoff is determined both by the place and by the number of other players choosing the same place.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] In a crowding game, given a strategy $P_{i}=\{e\}$ , player i experiences delay $d_{i,e}(x_{e})$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] If the player switches to a different strategy f, his delay would be $d_{i,f}(x_{f}+1)$ ; hence, a strategy vector is a PNE iff for every player i, $d_{i,e}(x_{e})\leq d_{i,f}(x_{f}+1)$ for all *e*,*f*.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] In general, CGs with player-specific delays might *not* admit a potential function.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] This shows that the finite-improvement property does not hold, so the game cannot have a potential function (not even a generalized-ordinal-potential function).
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] When there are three or more players, even best-response paths might be cyclic.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] The proof is constructive and shows an algorithm that finds a Nash equilibrium in at most ${n+1 \choose 2}$ steps.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Moreover, every CG is weakly acyclic: for any initial strategy-vector, at least one best-response path starting at this vector has a length of at most $r{n+1 \choose 2}$ , which terminates at an equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Every crowding game is *sequentially solvable*.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] This means that, for every ordering of the players, the sequential game in which each player in turn picks a strategy has a subgame-perfect equilibrium in which the players' actions are a PNE in the original simultaneous game.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Every crowding game has at least one strong PNE; every strong PNE of a crowding game can be attained as a subgame-perfect equilibrium of a sequential version of the game.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] In general, a crowding game might have many different PNE.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] For example, suppose there are *n* players and *n* resources, and the negative effect of congestion on the payoff is much higher than the positive value of the resources.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Then there are n! different PNEs: every one-to-one matching of players to resources is a PNE, as no player would move to a resource occupied by another player.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] However, if a crowding game is replicated *m* times, then the set of PNEs converges to a single point as *m* goes to infinity.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Moreover, in a "large" (nonatomic) crowding game, there is generically a unique PNE.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] This PNE has an interesting graph-theoretic property.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Let *G* be a bipartite graph with players on one side and resources on the other side, where each player is adjacent to all the resources that his copies choose in the unique PNE.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] A special case of the player-specific delay functions is that the delay functions can be separated into a player-specific factor and a general factor.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] When only pure-strategies are considered, these two notions are equivalent, since the logarithm of a product is a sum.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Moreover, when players may have resource-specific weights, the setting with resource-specific delay functions can be reduced to the setting with a universal delay function.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Games with separable cost functions occur in load-balancing, M/M/1 queueing, and habitat selection.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Every weighted *singleton* CG with separable player-specific preferences is isomorphic to a weighted *network* CG with player-independent preference.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Milchtaich considered the special case of CGs with player-specific costs, in which each strategy is a path in a given graph ("network CG").
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] He proved that every finite game can be represented as an (unweighted) network congestion game with player-specific costs, with nondecreasing (but not necessarily negative) cost-functions.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] A complete characterization of networks that guarantee the existence of PNE in such CGs is posed as an open problem.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] The proof of existence of PNE is constructive: it shows a finite algorithm (an improvement path) that always finds a PNE.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] This raises the question of how many steps are required to find this PNE?
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Even-Dar, Kesselman and Mansour analyze the number of steps required for convergence to equilibrium in a load-balancing setting.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Caragiannis, Fanelli, Gravin and Skopalik present an algorithm that computes a constant-factor approximation PNE.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Their algorithm identifies a short sequence of best-response moves, that leads to an approximate equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] They also show that, for more general CGs, attaining any polynomial approximation of PNE is PLS-complete.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Fotakis, Kontogiannis and Spirakis present an algorithm that, in any weighted network CG with linear delay functions, finds a PNE in pseudo-polynomial time (polynomial in the number of players *n* and the sum of players' weights *W*).
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Their algorithm is a greedy best-response algorithm: players enter the game in descending order of their weight, and choose a best-response to existing players' strategies.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Panagopoulou and Spirakis show empirical evidence that the algorithm of Fotakis, Kontogiannis and Spirakis in fact runs in time polynomial in *n* and log *W*.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] They also propose an initial strategy-vector that dramatically speeds this algorithm.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] In general, a weighted network CG may not have a PNE.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] The proof is by reduction from the directed edge-disjoint paths problem.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Caragiannis, Fanelli, Gravin and Skopalik present an algorithm that computes a constant-factor approximation PNE in weighted CGs.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] To prove their results, they show that, although weighted CGs may not have a potential function, every weighted CG can be *approximated* by a certain potential game.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] This lets them show that every weighted CG has a (*d*!)-approximate PNE.
[src:price-of-anarchy/congestion-game] Their algorithm identifies a short sequence of best-response moves, that leads to such an approximate PNE.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In game theory, a **Nash equilibrium** is a situation where no player could gain more by changing their own strategy (holding all other players' strategies fixed) in a game.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] A Nash equilibrium is the most commonly used solution concept for non-cooperative games.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In a game in which Carol and Dan are also players, (A, B, C, D) is a Nash equilibrium if A is Alice's best response to (B, C, D), B is Bob's best response to (A, C, D), and so forth.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The concept of a Nash equilibrium dates back to the time of Cournot, who in 1838 applied it to his model of competition in an oligopoly.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] John Nash showed that there is a Nash equilibrium, possibly in mixed strategies, for every finite game.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Game theorists use Nash equilibrium to analyze the outcome of the strategic interaction of several decision makers.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In a strategic interaction, the outcome for each decision-maker depends on the decisions of the others as well as their own.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The insight underlying Nash's idea is that one cannot predict the choices of multiple decision makers if one analyzes those decisions in isolation.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Instead, one must ask what each player would do taking into account what the player expects the others to do.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] A Nash equilibrium is achieved when no player can improve their outcome by changing their decision, assuming the other players' choices remain unchanged.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The concept has been used to analyze hostile situations such as wars and arms races (see prisoner's dilemma), and also how conflict may be mitigated by repeated interaction (see tit-for-tat).
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] It has also been used to study to what extent people with different preferences can cooperate (see battle of the sexes), and whether they will take risks to achieve a cooperative outcome (see stag hunt).
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] It has been used to study the adoption of technical standards, and also the occurrence of bank runs and currency crises (see coordination game).
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Nash equilibrium is named after American mathematician John Forbes Nash Jr.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The same idea was used in a particular application in 1838 by Antoine Augustin Cournot in his theory of oligopoly.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In Cournot's theory, each of several firms choose how much output to produce to maximize its profit.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The best output for one firm depends on the outputs of the others.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] A Cournot equilibrium occurs when each firm's output maximizes its profits given the output of the other firms, which is a pure-strategy Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Cournot also introduced the concept of best response dynamics in his analysis of the stability of equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Cournot did not use the idea in any other applications, however, or define it generally.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The modern concept of Nash equilibrium is instead defined in terms of mixed strategies, where players choose a probability distribution over possible pure strategies (which might put 100% of the probability on one pure strategy; such pure strategies are a subset of mixed strategies).
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The concept of a mixed-strategy equilibrium was introduced by John von Neumann and Oskar Morgenstern in their 1944 book *The Theory of Games and Economic Behavior*, but their analysis was restricted to the special case of zero-sum games.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] They showed that a mixed-strategy Nash equilibrium will exist for any zero-sum game with a finite set of actions.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The contribution of Nash in his 1951 article "Non-Cooperative Games" was to define a mixed-strategy Nash equilibrium for any game with a finite set of actions and prove that at least one (mixed-strategy) Nash equilibrium must exist in such a game.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The key to Nash's ability to prove existence far more generally than von Neumann lay in his definition of equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] According to Nash, "an equilibrium point is an n-tuple such that each player's mixed strategy maximizes [their] payoff if the strategies of the others are held fixed.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Thus each player's strategy is optimal against those of the others." Putting the problem in this framework allowed Nash to employ the Kakutani fixed-point theorem in his 1950 paper to prove existence of equilibria.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] His 1951 paper used the simpler Brouwer fixed-point theorem for the same purpose.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Game theorists have discovered that in some circumstances Nash equilibrium makes invalid predictions or fails to make a unique prediction.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] They have proposed many solution concepts ('refinements' of Nash equilibria) designed to rule out implausible Nash equilibria.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] One particularly important issue is that some Nash equilibria may be based on threats that are not 'credible'.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In 1965 Reinhard Selten proposed subgame perfect equilibrium as a refinement that eliminates equilibria which depend on non-credible threats.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Other extensions of the Nash equilibrium concept have addressed what happens if a game is repeated, or what happens if a game is played in the absence of complete information.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] However, subsequent refinements and extensions of Nash equilibrium share the main insight on which Nash's concept rests: the equilibrium is a set of strategies such that each player's strategy is optimal given the choices of the others.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] A strategy profile is a set of strategies, one for each player.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Informally, a strategy profile is a Nash equilibrium if no player can do better by unilaterally changing their strategy.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] To see what this means, imagine that each player is told the strategies of the others.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] For instance if a player prefers "Yes", then that set of strategies is not a Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] But if every player prefers not to switch (or is indifferent between switching and not) then the strategy profile is a Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Thus, each strategy in a Nash equilibrium is a best response to the other players' strategies in that equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Formally, let $S_{i}$ be the set of all possible strategies for player i , where $i=1,\ldots ,N$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Let $s^{*}=(s_{i}^{*},s_{-i}^{*})$ be a strategy profile, a set consisting of one strategy for each player, where $s_{-i}^{*}$ denotes the $N-1$ strategies of all the players except i .
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Let $u_{i}(s_{i},s_{-i}^{*})$ be player *i*'s payoff as a function of the strategies.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] A game can have more than one Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Even if the equilibrium is unique, it might be *weak*: a player might be indifferent among several strategies given the other players' choices.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The strategy set $S_{i}$ can be different for different players, and its elements can be a variety of mathematical objects.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Nash's existence proofs assume a finite strategy set, but the concept of Nash equilibrium does not require it.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] A game can have a pure-strategy or a mixed-strategy Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In the latter, not every player always plays the same strategy.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Instead, there is a probability distribution over different strategies.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] If every player's answer is "Yes", then the equilibrium is classified as a *strict Nash equilibrium*.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] If instead, for some player, there is exact equality between the strategy in Nash equilibrium and some other strategy that gives exactly the same payout (i.e., the player is indifferent between switching and not), then the equilibrium is classified as a *weak* or *non-strict Nash equilibrium*.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The Nash equilibrium defines stability only in terms of individual player deviations.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In cooperative games such a concept is not convincing enough.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Strong Nash equilibrium allows for deviations by every conceivable coalition.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Formally, a strong Nash equilibrium is a Nash equilibrium in which no coalition, taking the actions of its complements as given, can cooperatively deviate in a way that benefits all of its members.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] However, the strong Nash concept is sometimes perceived as too "strong" in that the environment allows for unlimited private communication.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In fact, strong Nash equilibrium has to be weakly Pareto efficient.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] As a result of these requirements, strong Nash is too rare to be useful in many branches of game theory.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] However, in games such as elections with many more players than possible outcomes, it can be more common than a stable equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] A refined Nash equilibrium known as coalition-proof Nash equilibrium (CPNE) occurs when players cannot do better even if they are allowed to communicate and make "self-enforcing" agreement to deviate.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Every correlated strategy supported by iterated strict dominance and on the Pareto frontier is a CPNE.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Further, it is possible for a game to have a Nash equilibrium that is resilient against coalitions less than a specified size, k.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] CPNE is related to the theory of the core.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Nash equilibria need not exist if the set of choices is infinite and non-compact.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] However, a Nash equilibrium exists if the set of choices is compact with each player's payoff continuous in the strategies of all the players.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Nash's existence theorem has been extended to more general classes of games.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In Nash's model, the set of strategies available to each player is fixed and does not depend on the other players' strategies.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] A more general model allows these sets to depend on other players' strategies; this is often called **coupled constraints**.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In Nash's model, the set of possible strategy-profiles is a Cartesian product of the players' strategy sets, whereas in the more general model it can be an arbitrary set.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] When there are coupled constraints, the equilibrium is often called **Generalized Nash equilibrium** **(GNE)**.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Rosen proved that, if the set of strategy-profiles is any convex set, and the utility function of each player is continuous in all strategies and a concave function of the player's own strategy, then a GNE exists; see **concave games**.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Nash considered games with finitely many players, in **non-atomic games** the set of players is infinite - there is a continuum of players David Schmeidler proved that an equilibrium exists under certain conditions.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The Nash equilibrium may sometimes appear non-rational in a third-person perspective.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] This is because a Nash equilibrium is not necessarily Pareto optimal.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Nash equilibrium may also have non-rational consequences in sequential games because players may "threaten" each other with threats they would not actually carry out.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] For such games the subgame perfect Nash equilibrium may be more meaningful as a tool of analysis.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The *coordination game* is a classic two-player, two-strategy game, as shown in the example payoff matrix to the right.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] There are two pure-strategy equilibria, (A,A) with payoff 4 for each player and (B,B) with payoff 2 for each.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The combination (B,B) is a Nash equilibrium because if either player unilaterally changes their strategy from B to A, their payoff will fall from 2 to 1.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] A famous example of a coordination game is the stag hunt.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Two players may choose to hunt a stag or a rabbit, the stag providing more meat (4 utility units, 2 for each player) than the rabbit (1 utility unit).
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The caveat is that the stag must be cooperatively hunted, so if one player attempts to hunt the stag, while the other hunts the rabbit, the stag hunter will totally fail, for a payoff of 0, whereas the rabbit hunter will succeed, for a payoff of 1.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The game has two equilibria, (stag, stag) and (rabbit, rabbit), because a player's optimal strategy depends on their expectation on what the other player will do.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] If one hunter trusts that the other will hunt the stag, they should hunt the stag; however if they think the other will hunt the rabbit, they too will hunt the rabbit.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] This game is used as an analogy for social cooperation, since much of the benefit that people gain in society depends upon people cooperating and implicitly trusting one another to act in a manner corresponding with cooperation.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Driving on a road against an oncoming car, and having to choose either to swerve on the left or to swerve on the right of the road, is also a coordination game.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In this case there are two pure-strategy Nash equilibria, when both choose to either drive on the left or on the right.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] We add another where the probabilities for each player are (50%, 50%).
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] An application of Nash equilibria is in determining the expected flow of traffic in a network.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] If we assume that there are x "cars" traveling from A to D, what is the expected distribution of traffic in the network?
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] This situation can be modeled as a "game", where every traveler has a choice of 3 strategies and where each strategy is a route from A to D (one of ABD, ABCD, or ACD).
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The "payoff" of each strategy is the travel time of each route.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In the graph on the right, a car travelling via ABD experiences travel time of $1+{\frac {x}{100}}+2$ , where x is the number of cars traveling on edge AB.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Thus, payoffs for any given strategy depend on the choices of the other players, as is usual.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] However, the goal, in this case, is to minimize travel time, not maximize it.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Equilibrium will occur when the time on all paths is exactly the same.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] When that happens, no single driver has any incentive to switch routes, since it can only add to their travel time.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] For the graph on the right, if, for example, 100 cars are travelling from A to D, then equilibrium will occur when 25 drivers travel via ABD, 50 via ABCD, and 25 via ACD.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Every driver now has a total travel time of 3.75 (to see this, a total of 75 cars take the AB edge, and likewise, 75 cars take the CD edge).
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Notice that this distribution is not, actually, socially optimal.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] If the 100 cars agreed that 50 travel via ABD and the other 50 through ACD, then travel time for any single car would actually be 3.5, which is less than 3.75.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] This is also the Nash equilibrium if the path between B and C is removed, which means that adding another possible route can decrease the efficiency of the system, a phenomenon known as Braess's paradox.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] This can be illustrated by a two-player game in which both players simultaneously choose an integer from 0 to 3 and they both win the smaller of the two numbers in points.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In addition, if one player chooses a larger number than the other, then they have to give up two points to the other.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] This game has a unique pure-strategy Nash equilibrium: both players choosing 0 (highlighted in light red).
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Any other strategy can be improved by a player switching their number to one less than that of the other player.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In the adjacent table, if the game begins at the green square, it is in player 1's interest to move to the purple square and it is in player 2's interest to move to the blue square.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Although it would not fit the definition of a competition game, if the game is modified so that the two players win the named amount if they both choose the same number, and otherwise win nothing, then there are 4 Nash equilibria: (0,0), (1,1), (2,2), and (3,3).
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] There is an easy numerical way to identify Nash equilibria on a payoff matrix.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] It is especially helpful in two-person games where players have more than two strategies.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In this case formal analysis may become too long.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] This rule does not apply to the case where mixed (stochastic) strategies are of interest.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The rule goes as follows: if the first payoff number, in the payoff pair of the cell, is the maximum of the column of the cell and if the second number is the maximum of the row of the cell – then the cell represents a Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Using the rule, we can very quickly (much faster than with formal analysis) see that the Nash equilibria cells are (B,A), (A,B), and (C,C).
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Indeed, for cell (B,A), 40 is the maximum of the first column and 25 is the maximum of the second row.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] For (A,B), 25 is the maximum of the second column and 40 is the maximum of the first row; the same applies for cell (C,C).
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] For other cells, either one or both of the duplet members are not the maximum of the corresponding rows and columns.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] This said, the actual mechanics of finding equilibrium cells is obvious: find the maximum of a column and check if the second member of the pair is the maximum of the row.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] If these conditions are met, the cell represents a Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Check all columns this way to find all NE cells.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] An N×N matrix may have between 0 and N×N pure-strategy Nash equilibria.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The concept of stability, useful in the analysis of many kinds of equilibria, can also be applied to Nash equilibria.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] 2. the player who did change is now playing with a strictly worse strategy.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] If these cases are both met, then a player with the small change in their mixed strategy will return immediately to the Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] If condition one does not hold then the equilibrium is unstable.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] If only condition one holds then there are likely to be an infinite number of optimal strategies for the player who changed.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In the "driving game" example above there are both stable and unstable equilibria.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The equilibria involving mixed strategies with 100% probabilities are stable.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] If either player changes their probabilities slightly, they will be both at a disadvantage, and their opponent will have no reason to change their strategy in turn.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] If either player changes their probabilities (which would neither benefit or damage the expectation of the player who did the change, if the other player's mixed strategy is still (50%,50%)), then the other player immediately has a better strategy at either (0%, 100%) or (100%, 0%).
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Stability is crucial in practical applications of Nash equilibria, since the mixed strategy of each player is not perfectly known, but has to be inferred from statistical distribution of their actions in the game.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In this case unstable equilibria are very unlikely to arise in practice, since any minute change in the proportions of each strategy seen will lead to a change in strategy and the breakdown of the equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Finally in the eighties, building with great depth on such ideas Mertens-stable equilibria were introduced as a solution concept.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Mertens stable equilibria satisfy both forward induction and backward induction.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In a game theory context stable equilibria now usually refer to Mertens stable equilibria.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] If a game has a unique Nash equilibrium and is played among players under certain conditions, then the NE strategy set will be adopted.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The players have sufficient intelligence to deduce the solution.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The players know the planned equilibrium strategy of all of the other players.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The players believe that a deviation in their own strategy will not cause deviations by any other players.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] There is common knowledge that all players meet these conditions, including this one.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] So, not only must each player know the other players meet the conditions, but also they must know that they all know that they meet them, and know that they know that they know that they meet them, and so on.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Intentional or accidental imperfection in execution.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] For example, a computer capable of flawless logical play facing a second flawless computer will result in equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Introduction of imperfection will lead to its disruption either through loss to the player who makes the mistake, or through negation of the common knowledge criterion leading to possible victory for the player.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] (An example would be a player suddenly putting the car into reverse in the game of chicken, ensuring a no-loss no-win scenario).
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In many cases, the third condition is not met because, even though the equilibrium must exist, it is unknown due to the complexity of the game, for instance in Chinese chess.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Or, if known, it may not be known to all players, as when playing tic-tac-toe with a small child who desperately wants to win (meeting the other criteria).
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The criterion of common knowledge may not be met even if all players do, in fact, meet all the other criteria.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Players wrongly distrusting each other's rationality may adopt counter-strategies to expected irrational play on their opponents’ behalf.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] This is a major consideration in "chicken" or an arms race, for example.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In his Ph.D. dissertation, John Nash proposed two interpretations of his equilibrium concept, with the objective of showing how equilibrium points can be connected with observable phenomena.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In this case, the conjectures need only be mutually known).
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] For a formal result along these lines, see Kuhn, H. and et al., 1996, "The Work of John Nash in Game Theory", *Journal of Economic Theory*, 69, 153–185.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Due to the limited conditions in which NE can actually be observed, they are rarely treated as a guide to day-to-day behaviour, or observed in practice in human negotiations.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] However, as a theoretical concept in economics and evolutionary biology, the NE has explanatory power.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The payoff in economics is utility (or sometimes money), and in evolutionary biology is gene transmission; both are the fundamental bottom line of survival.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Researchers who apply games theory in these fields claim that strategies failing to maximize these for whatever reason will be competed out of the market or environment, which are ascribed the ability to test all strategies.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] This conclusion is drawn from the "stability" theory above.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In these situations the assumption that the strategy observed is actually a NE has often been borne out by research.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The Nash equilibrium is a superset of the subgame perfect Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The subgame perfect equilibrium in addition to the Nash equilibrium requires that the strategy also is a Nash equilibrium in every subgame of that game.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] This eliminates all non-credible threats, that is, strategies that contain non-rational moves in order to make the counter-player change their strategy.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The image to the right shows a simple sequential game that illustrates the issue with subgame imperfect Nash equilibria.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In this game player one chooses left(L) or right(R), which is followed by player two being called upon to be kind (K) or unkind (U) to player one, However, player two only stands to gain from being unkind if player one goes left.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] If player one goes right the rational player two would de facto be kind to her/him in that subgame.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] However, The non-credible threat of being unkind at 2(2) is still part of the blue (L, (U,U)) Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Therefore, if rational behavior can be expected by both parties the subgame perfect Nash equilibrium may be a more meaningful solution concept when such dynamic inconsistencies arise.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Nash's original proof (in his thesis) used Brouwer's fixed-point theorem (e.g., see below for a variant).
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] This section presents a simpler proof via the Kakutani fixed-point theorem, following Nash's 1950 paper (he credits David Gale with the observation that such a simplification is possible).
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Here, $\sigma \in \Sigma$ , where $\Sigma =\Sigma _{i}\times \Sigma _{-i}$ , is a mixed-strategy profile in the set of all mixed strategies and $u_{i}$ is the payoff function for player i.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Define a set-valued function $r\colon \Sigma \rightarrow 2^{\Sigma }$ such that $r=r_{i}(\sigma _{-i})\times r_{-i}(\sigma _{i})$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The existence of a Nash equilibrium is equivalent to r having a fixed point.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Kakutani's fixed point theorem guarantees the existence of a fixed point if the following four conditions are satisfied.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Condition 1. is satisfied from the fact that $\Sigma$ is a simplex and thus compact.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Convexity follows from players' ability to mix strategies. $\Sigma$ is nonempty as long as players have strategies.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Condition 2. and 3. are satisfied by way of Berge's maximum theorem.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Because $u_{i}$ is continuous and compact, $r(\sigma _{i})$ is non-empty and upper hemicontinuous.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Condition 4. is satisfied as a result of mixed strategies.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Suppose $\sigma _{i},\sigma '_{i}\in r(\sigma _{-i})$ , then $\lambda \sigma _{i}+(1-\lambda )\sigma '_{i}\in r(\sigma _{-i})$ . i.e. if two strategies maximize payoffs, then a mix between the two strategies will yield the same payoff.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Therefore, there exists a fixed point in r and a Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] When Nash made this point to John von Neumann in 1949, von Neumann famously dismissed it with the words, "That's trivial, you know.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] That's just a fixed-point theorem." (See Nasar, 1998, p.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] We have a game $G=(N,A,u)$ where N is the number of players and $A=A_{1}\times \cdots \times A_{N}$ is the action set for the players.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] All of the action sets $A_{i}$ are finite.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Let $\Delta =\Delta _{1}\times \cdots \times \Delta _{N}$ denote the set of mixed strategies for the players.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The finiteness of the $A_{i}$ s ensures the compactness of $\Delta$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The gain function represents the benefit a player gets by unilaterally changing their strategy.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] It is easy to see that each $f_{i}$ is a valid mixed strategy in $\Delta _{i}$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] It is also easy to check that each $f_{i}$ is a continuous function of $\sigma$ , and hence f is a continuous function.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] As the cross product of a finite number of compact convex sets, $\Delta$ is also compact and convex.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Applying the Brouwer fixed point theorem to f and $\Delta$ we conclude that f has a fixed point in $\Delta$ , call it $\sigma ^{*}$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] We claim that $\sigma ^{*}$ is a Nash equilibrium in G .
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] This simply states that each player gains no benefit by unilaterally changing their strategy, which is exactly the necessary condition for a Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Now assume that the gains are not all zero.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Also we shall denote ${\text{Gain}}(i,\cdot )$ as the gain vector indexed by actions in $A_{i}$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Since $C>1$ we have that $\sigma _{i}^{*}$ is some positive scaling of the vector ${\text{Gain}}_{i}(\sigma ^{*},\cdot )$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] To see this, first if ${\text{Gain}}_{i}(\sigma ^{*},a)>0$ then this is true by definition of the gain function.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] and so the left term is zero, giving us that the entire expression is 0 as needed.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] where the last inequality follows since $\sigma _{i}^{*}$ is a non-zero vector.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] But this is a clear contradiction, so all the gains must indeed be zero.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Therefore, $\sigma ^{*}$ is a Nash equilibrium for G as needed.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] If a player A has a dominant strategy $s_{A}$ then there exists a Nash equilibrium in which A plays $s_{A}$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In the case of two players A and B, there exists a Nash equilibrium in which A plays $s_{A}$ and B plays a best response to $s_{A}$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] If $s_{A}$ is a strictly dominant strategy, A plays $s_{A}$ in all Nash equilibria.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] If both A and B have strictly dominant strategies, there exists a unique Nash equilibrium in which each plays their strictly dominant strategy.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In games with mixed-strategy Nash equilibria, the probability of a player choosing any particular (so pure) strategy can be computed by assigning a variable to each strategy that represents a fixed probability for choosing that strategy.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In order for a player to be willing to randomize, their expected payoff for each (pure) strategy should be the same.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In addition, the sum of the probabilities for each strategy of a particular player should be 1.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] This creates a system of equations from which the probabilities of choosing each strategy can be derived.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In the matching pennies game, player A loses a point to B if A and B play the same strategy and wins a point from B if they play different strategies.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] To compute the mixed-strategy Nash equilibrium, assign A the probability p of playing H and $(1-p)$ of playing T, and assign B the probability q of playing H and $(1-q)$ of playing T.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Thus, a mixed-strategy Nash equilibrium in this game is for each player to randomly choose H or T with $p={\frac {1}{2}}$ and $q={\frac {1}{2}}$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In 1971, Robert Wilson came up with the "oddness theorem", which says that "almost all" finite games have a finite and odd number of Nash equilibria.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In 1973, Harsanyi published an alternative proof of the result.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] "Almost all" here means that any game with an infinite or even number of equilibria is very special in the sense that if its payoffs were even slightly randomly perturbed, with probability one it would have an odd number of equilibria instead.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The prisoner's dilemma, for example, has one equilibrium, while the battle of the sexes has three—two pure and one mixed, and this remains true even if the payoffs change slightly.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] The free money game is an example of a "special" game with an even number of equilibria.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In it, two players have to both vote "yes" rather than "no" to get a reward and the votes are simultaneous.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] There are two pure-strategy Nash equilibria, (yes, yes) and (no, no), and no mixed strategy equilibria, because the strategy "yes" weakly dominates "no".
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] "Yes" is as good as "no" regardless of the other player's action, but if there is any chance the other player chooses "yes" then "yes" is the best reply.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Under a small random perturbation of the payoffs, however, the probability that any two payoffs would remain tied, whether at 0 or some other number, is vanishingly small, and the game would have either one or three equilibria instead.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In 1950 Nash proved that every n -person normal form game has a Nash equilibrium (NE) in mixed strategies.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Yet, there are large families of games that have NE in pure strategies, for example, finite n -person positional (graphical) games with perfect information.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] In case of two players, Nash solvability in pure strategies is equivalent to duality of hypergraphs.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Later this result was extended for the non-zero sum case.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Interestingly, in such NE the strategy of one player doesn't depend on the preferences of the other.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] But the opposite is not necessarily true.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] One can check all 4 pure-strategy profiles (the 4 cells in the matrix), and verify that in all of them, one of the players has a profitable deviation, so there is no Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] On the other hand, the minimax value of the row player is 1 (R-T) and the minimax value of the column player is 1 (B-R).
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] Hence, the strategy profile R-T is minmax-acceptable.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] There are games in which even a minmax-acceptable strategy profile does not exist.
[src:price-of-anarchy/nash-equilibrium] For example, in Matching pennies, the minimax values (with pure strategies) are 1,1, but the sum of payments is 0, so no strategy profile can give 1 to both players.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] In game theory, a game is said to be a **potential game** if the incentive of all players to change their strategy can be expressed using a single global function called the **potential function**.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] The concept originated in a 1996 paper by Dov Monderer and Lloyd Shapley.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] The properties of several types of potential games have since been studied.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] Games can be either *ordinal* or *cardinal* potential games.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] In cardinal games, the difference in individual payoffs for each player from individually changing one's strategy, other things equal, has to have the same value as the difference in values for the potential function.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] In ordinal games, only the signs of the differences have to be the same.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] The potential function is a useful tool to analyze equilibrium properties of games, since the incentives of all players are mapped into one function, and the set of pure Nash equilibria can be found by locating the local optima of the potential function.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] Convergence and finite-time convergence of an iterated game towards a Nash equilibrium can also be understood by studying the potential function.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] Potential games can be studied as repeated games with state so that every round played has a direct consequence on game's state in the next round.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] This approach has applications in distributed control such as distributed resource allocation, where players without a central correlation mechanism can cooperate to achieve a globally optimal resource distribution.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] Let N be the number of players, A the set of action profiles over the action sets $A_{i}$ of each player and $u_{i}:A\to \mathbb {R}$ be the payoff function for player $1\leq i\leq N$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] equals the change in the utility of that player.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] equals the change in the player's utility, times a positive player-specific weight.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] of the change in the player's utility, whereas the magnitude of change may differ.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] That is: when a player switches action, if the player's utility increases, then the potential increases (but the opposite is not necessarily true).
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] Every ordinal PF is a generalized-ordinal PF.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] , maximizing the common potential function leads to the same outcome as maximizing his own utility.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] Note that while there are N utility functions, one for each player, there is only one potential function.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] Thus, through the lens of potential functions, the players become interchangeable (in the sense of one of the definitions above).
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] Because of this *symmetry* of the game, decentralized algorithms based on the shared potential function often lead to convergence (in some of sense) to a Nash equilibria.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] In *a* 2-player, 2-action game with externalities, individual players' payoffs are given by the function *u**i*(*a**i*, *a**j*) = *b**i* *a**i* + *w* *a**i* *a**j*, where *a**i* is players i's action, *a**j* is the opponent's action, and *w* is *a* positive externality from choosing the same action.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] The action choices are +1 and −1, as seen in the payoff matrix in Figure 1.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] The solution for player 2 is equivalent.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] Using numerical values *b*1 = 2, *b*2 = −1, *w* = 3, this example transforms into *a* simple battle of the sexes, as shown in Figure 2.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] The game has two pure Nash equilibria, (+1, +1) and (−1, −1).
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] These are also the local maxima of the potential function (Figure 3).
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] The only stochastically stable equilibrium is (+1, +1), the global maximum of the potential function.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] Exact potential games are equivalent to congestion games: Rosenthal proved that every congestion game has an exact potential; Monderer and Shapley proved the opposite direction: every game with an exact potential function is a congestion game.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] The class of *ordinal* potential games is much larger.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] Fabrikant, Papadimitriou and Talwar proved that, for every problem in the complexity class PLS (essentially, every local search problem), there exists an ordinal potential game with polynomially many players, such that the set of pure Nash equilibria equals the set of local optima.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] An **improvement path** (also called **Nash dynamics**) is a sequence of strategy-vectors, in which each vector is attained from the previous vector by a single player switching his strategy to a strategy that strictly increases his utility.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] If a game has a generalized-ordinal-potential function $\Phi$ , then $\Phi$ is strictly increasing in every improvement path, so every improvement path is acyclic.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] If, in addition, the game has finitely many strategies, then every improvement path must be finite.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] This property is called the **finite improvement property (FIP)**.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] We have just proved that every finite generalized-ordinal-potential game has the FIP.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] The opposite is also true: every finite game has the FIP has a generalized-ordinal-potential function.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] The terminal state in every finite improvement path is a Nash equilibrium, so FIP implies the existence of a pure-strategy Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] Moreover, it implies that a Nash equilibrium can be computed by a distributed process, in which each agent only has to improve his own strategy.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] A **best-response path** is a special case of an improvement path, in which each vector is attained from the previous vector by a single player switching his strategy to a best-response strategy.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] The property that every best-response path is finite is called the **finite best-response property (FBRP)**.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] FBRP is weaker than FIP, and it still implies the existence of a pure-strategy Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] It also implies that a Nash equilibrium can be computed by a distributed process, but the computational burden on the agents is higher than with FIP, since they have to compute a best-response.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] An even weaker property is **weak-acyclicity (WA)**.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] It means that, for any initial strategy-vector, *there exists* a finite best-response path starting at that vector.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] Weak-acyclicity is not sufficient for existence of a potential function (since some improvement-paths may be cyclic), but it is sufficient for the existence of pure-strategy Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] It implies that a Nash equilibrium can be computed almost-surely by a stochastic distributed process, in which at each point, a player is chosen at random, and this player chooses a best-strategy at random.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] Abraham Neyman studied potential games in which (a) the potential is a smooth and concave function, (b) the strategy sets are convex, (c) the utilities are bounded.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] He proves that, in such games, any correlated equilibrium is a mixture of pure strategy profiles which maximize the potential.
[src:price-of-anarchy/potential-game] If, in addition, (d) the strategy sets are compact, (e) the potential is a strictly concave function, then the correlated equilibrium is unique.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] The **Price of Anarchy** (**PoA**) is a concept in economics and game theory that measures how the efficiency of a system degrades due to selfish behavior of its agents.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] It is a general notion that can be extended to diverse systems and notions of efficiency.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] For example, consider the system of transportation of a city and many agents trying to go from some initial location to a destination.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] Here, efficiency means the average time for an agent to reach the destination.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] In the 'centralized' solution, a central authority can tell each agent which path to take in order to minimize the average travel time.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] In the 'decentralized' version, each agent chooses its own path.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] The Price of Anarchy measures the ratio between average travel time in the two cases.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] Usually the system is modeled as a game and the efficiency is some function of the outcomes (e.g. maximum delay in a network, congestion in a transportation system, social welfare in an auction, etc.).
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] Different concepts of equilibrium can be used to model the selfish behavior of the agents, among which the most common is the Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] Different flavors of Nash equilibrium lead to variations of the notion of Price of Anarchy as **Pure Price of Anarchy** (for deterministic equilibria), **Mixed Price of Anarchy** (for randomized equilibria), and **Bayes–Nash Price of Anarchy** (for games with incomplete information).
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] Solution concepts other than Nash equilibrium lead to variations such as the **Price of Sinking**.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] The term Price of Anarchy was first used by Elias Koutsoupias and Christos Papadimitriou, but the idea of measuring inefficiency of equilibrium is older.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] The concept in its current form was designed to be the analogue of the 'approximation ratio' in an approximation algorithm or the 'competitive ratio' in an online algorithm.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] This is in the context of the current trend of analyzing games using algorithmic lenses (algorithmic game theory).
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] Consider a game $G=(N,S,u)$ , defined by a set of players N , strategy sets $S_{i}$ for each player and utilities $u_{i}:S\rightarrow \mathbb {R}$ (where $S=S_{1}\times ...\times S_{n}$ also called set of outcomes).
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] We can define a measure of efficiency of each outcome which we call welfare function $\operatorname {Welf} :S\rightarrow \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] We can define a subset $Equil\subseteq S$ to be the set of strategies in equilibrium (for example, the set of Nash equilibria).
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] We know that $1\leq PoS\leq PoA$ by the definition.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] It is expected that the loss in efficiency due to game-theoretical constraints is somewhere between 'PoS' and 'PoA'.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] However, the highest social welfare occurs when both cooperate, in which case the cost is $C_{min}=1+1=2$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] Thus the PoA of this game will be $C_{equil}/C_{min}=10/2=5$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] Since the game has a unique Nash equilibrium, the PoS is equal to the PoA and it is 5 too.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] A more natural example is the one of **job scheduling**.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] There are N players and each of them has a job to run.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] They can choose one of M machines to run the job.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] The Price of Anarchy compares the situation where the selection of machines is guided/directed centrally to the situation where each player chooses the machine that will make its job run fastest.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] Each machine has a speed $s_{1},\ldots ,s_{M}>0.$ Each job has a weight $w_{1},\ldots ,w_{N}>0.$ A player picks a machine to run his or her job on.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] The cost for player i is $c_{i}(a)=L_{a_{i}}(a),$ i.e., the load of the machine they chose.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] We consider two concepts of equilibrium: pure Nash and mixed Nash.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] First we need to argue that there exist pure Nash equilibria.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] We claim that this is a pure-strategy Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] Reasoning by contradiction, suppose that some player i could strictly improve by moving from machine j to machine k .
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] This means that the increased load of machine k after the move is still smaller than the load of machine j before the move.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] As the load of machine j must decrease as a result of the move and no other machine is affected, this means that the new configuration is guaranteed to have reduced the j th-largest (or higher ranked) load in the distribution.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] Since the above holds for the social optimum as well, comparing the ratios $w(\sigma )$ and $w(a)$ proves the claim.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] Consider a road network as shown in the adjacent diagram on which 4000 drivers wish to travel from point Start to End.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] The travel time in minutes on the Start–A road is the number of travelers (T) divided by 100, and on Start–B is a constant 45 minutes (likewise with the roads across from them).
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] If the dashed road does not exist (so the traffic network has 4 roads in total), the time needed to drive Start–A–End route with a drivers would be ${\tfrac {a}{100}}+45$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] Now suppose the dashed line A–B is a road with an extremely short travel time of approximately 0 minutes.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] The routing problem introduced in the Braess's paradox can be generalized to many different flows traversing the same graph at the same time.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] For succinctness, we write $f_{e}$ when $\Gamma ,R$ are clear from context.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] This definition is closely related to what we said about the support of mixed-strategy Nash equilibria in normal-form games.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] In other words, the flow $f^{*}$ can achieve a lower welfare than f only if there are two paths from $s_{i}$ to $t_{i}$ having different costs, and if $f^{*}$ reroutes some flow of f from the higher-cost path to the lower-cost path.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] Note that Fact 1 does not assume any particular structure on the set L .
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] Note that in the proof we have made extensive use of the assumption that the functions in L are linear.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] This quantity tends to zero when d tends to infinity.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] PoA upper bounds can be obtained if the game is shown to satisfy a so-called *smoothness* inequality.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] In this case, the PoA is upper bounded by *λ*/(1 − *μ*).
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] For cost-sharing games with concave cost functions, the optimal cost-sharing rule that optimizes the price of anarchy, followed by the price of stability, is precisely the Shapley value cost-sharing rule.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] (A symmetrical statement is similarly valid for utility-sharing games with convex utility functions.) In mechanism design, this means that the Shapley value solution concept is optimal for these sets of games.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-anarchy] Moreover, for these (finite) games it was proven that every equilibrium which achieves the PoA bound is fragile, in the sense that the agents demonstrate a state of indifference between their equilibrium action and the action they would pursue in a system-optimal outcome.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] In game theory, the **price of stability (PoS)** of a game is the ratio between the best objective function value of one of its equilibria and that of an optimal outcome.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] The PoS is relevant for games in which there is some objective authority that can influence the players a bit, and maybe help them converge to a good Nash equilibrium.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] When measuring how efficient a Nash equilibrium is in a specific game we often also talk about the price of anarchy (PoA), which is the ratio between the *worst* objective function value of one of its equilibria and that of an optimal outcome.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] In particular, if the optimal solution is a Nash equilibrium, then the PoS is 1.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] In the following prisoner’s dilemma game, since there is a single equilibrium $(B,R)$ we have PoS = PoA = 1/2.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] On this example which is a version of the battle of sexes game, there are two equilibrium points, $(T,L)$ and $(B,R)$ , with values 3 and 15, respectively.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] The price of stability was first studied by A.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] Stier-Moses, while the term was coined by E.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] Schulz and Stier-Moses focused on equilibria in a selfish routing game in which edges have capacities.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] Anshelevich et al. studied network design games and showed that a pure strategy Nash equilibrium always exists with the price of stability in this game being at most the nth harmonic number in directed graphs.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] For undirected graphs, Anshelevich et al. presented a tight bound on the price of stability of 4/3 for a single source and two players case.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] Jian Li has proved that for undirected graphs with a distinguished destination to which all players must connect the price of stability of the Shapely network design game is $O(\log n/\log \log n)$ where n is the number of players.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] On the other hand, the price of anarchy is about n in this game.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] Network design games have a very natural motivation for the Price of Stability.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] In these games, the Price of Anarchy can be much worse than the Price of Stability.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] The price of anarchy can be $\Omega (n)$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] Consider the following network design game.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] Consider two different equilibria in this game.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] If everyone shares the $1+\varepsilon$ edge, the social cost is $1+\varepsilon$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] Note, however, that everyone sharing the n edge is a Nash equilibrium as well.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] Each agent has cost 1 at equilibrium, and switching to the other edge raises his cost to $1+\varepsilon$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] Here is a pathological game in the same spirit for the Price of Stability, instead.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] Consider n players, each originating from $s_{i}$ and trying to connect to t .
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] The cost of unlabeled edges is taken to be 0.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] The optimal strategy is for everyone to share the $1+\varepsilon$ edge, yielding total social cost $1+\varepsilon$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] However, there is a unique Nash for this game.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] Note that when at the optimum, each player is paying $\textstyle {\frac {1+\varepsilon }{n}}$ , and player 1 can decrease his cost by switching to the $\textstyle {\frac {1}{n}}$ edge.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] Once this has happened, it will be in player 2's interest to switch to the $\textstyle {\frac {1}{n-1}}$ edge, and so on.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] Eventually, the agents will reach the Nash equilibrium of paying for their own edge.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] This allocation has social cost $\textstyle 1+{\frac {1}{2}}+\cdots +{\frac {1}{n}}=H_{n}$ , where $H_{n}$ is the n th harmonic number, which is $\Theta (\log n)$ .
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] Even though it is unbounded, the price of stability is exponentially better than the price of anarchy in this game.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] Note that by design, network design games are congestion games.
[src:price-of-anarchy/price-of-stability] We trivially have $A=1$ , and the computation above gives $B=H_{n}$ , so we may invoke the theorem for an upper bound on the price of stability.
